Question:
Flatten a list of integer lists into a unique set.

Input:
List<List<Integer>> listOfLists = Arrays.asList(Arrays.asList(1,2), Arrays.asList(2,3,4));

Solutions:-

Java 8 Streams flatten nested integer lists into unique set using flatMap + collect(toSet()). For input [[1,2], [2,3,4]], produces {1,2,3,4}.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream outer list → flatMap(inner -> inner.stream()) → collect(Collectors.toSet()).

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.*;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class FlattenToUniqueSet {
    public static Set<Integer> flattenToUniqueSet(List<List<Integer>> listOfLists) {
        return listOfLists.stream()
                         .flatMap(List::stream)           // flatten nested lists
                         .collect(Collectors.toSet());    // unique HashSet
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<List<Integer>> listOfLists = Arrays.asList(
            Arrays.asList(1, 2),
            Arrays.asList(2, 3, 4)
        );
        
        Set<Integer> result = flattenToUniqueSet(listOfLists);
        System.out.println(result);  // [1, 2, 3, 4]
    }
}

#Thought Process
flatMap(List::stream): Converts each List<Integer> → Stream<Integer>, flattening nested structure.
collect(toSet()): Automatic deduplication via HashSet (equals/hashCode).
Order: Unordered (HashSet). Use LinkedHashSet for insertion order.
Single-pass O(n): One traversal flattens + deduplicates.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty outer: Empty Set
Empty inner lists: Skipped (empty streams)
All duplicates: Single element set
Null outer: NPE on stream()
Null inner list: null.stream() NPE
Null elements: HashSet handles null once
